<div id="review_1300267965" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1300267965" />
    <a title="Kavita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita"><img alt="Kavita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1315387023p2/5858699.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1300267965?book_show_action=true">Jun 06, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kavita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kavita" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita">Kavita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=uk">uk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=ghosts-and-horror">ghosts-and-horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1300267965" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6918571492360541977">I somehow prefer Victorian horror and ghost stories to anything modern, even though there are some modern horror authors that I like. In the oldie books, they didn&apos;t think they had to be &apos;clever&apos; or gory in order to induce the creeps. The stories in this book are chilling and frightening, merely by the existence of the supernatural and the deliberate erasing out of the gore. <br/><br/>My favourite has to be <i>The Mezzotint</i>, a story about a creepy painting that comes to life. Another one is <i>The Diary of Mr. </i></span>
  <span id="freeText6918571492360541977" style="display:none">I somehow prefer Victorian horror and ghost stories to anything modern, even though there are some modern horror authors that I like. In the oldie books, they didn't think they had to be 'clever' or gory in order to induce the creeps. The stories in this book are chilling and frightening, merely by the existence of the supernatural and the deliberate erasing out of the gore. <br /><br />My favourite has to be <i>The Mezzotint</i>, a story about a creepy painting that comes to life. Another one is <i>The Diary of Mr. Poyntner</i>, about a cloth pattern that proves to be not so benign as one would think. The others are just as entertaining and scary. What makes it more fun is that these stories usually are set in a very peaceful background where you wouldn't think anything bad ever happens. Except that it does. <br /><br />There are more than 30 short stories in the book, each more delightful than the last. But I found the last six or seven stories didn't really match up to the rest. They were too short and weren't really much of a story either, more like short sketches that were not too scary or interesting. So striking off one star. But otherwise, this book is a great collection of ghost stories, not for the faint of heart.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6918571492360541977" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


