    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_802432223" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/802432223" />
    <a title="Joe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/715626-joe"><img alt="Joe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1366845516p2/715626.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/802432223?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe" href="/user/show/715626-joe">Joe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer802432223" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6903733433058654043">M.R. James wrote antiquarian scary stories and was a huge influence on H.P. Lovecraft. I&apos;d previously read one of his stories in an anthology so I figured in the spirit of the cold and dark days of winter being a perfect time for scary stories, I decided to read a set of his complete ghost stories. Below are some snippet reviews of each story.<br/><br/>Canon Alberic&apos;s Scrap-Book: A scholar spends time with a skittish overseer in a dilapidated cathedral photographing the interior. He acts a bit too cavalie</span>
  <span id="freeText6903733433058654043" style="display:none">M.R. James wrote antiquarian scary stories and was a huge influence on H.P. Lovecraft. I'd previously read one of his stories in an anthology so I figured in the spirit of the cold and dark days of winter being a perfect time for scary stories, I decided to read a set of his complete ghost stories. Below are some snippet reviews of each story.<br /><br />Canon Alberic's Scrap-Book: A scholar spends time with a skittish overseer in a dilapidated cathedral photographing the interior. He acts a bit too cavalierly and gets his just desserts.<br /> <br />Lost Hearts: A recent orphan goes to live with an eccentric and much older cousin. There is a strange temple attached to the house and the orphan begins to hear, see, and feel strange things during the night. Just what is the cousin up to and why? Super creepy with a very satisfying ending.<br /> <br />The Mezzotint: A Mezzotint was an early kind of picture/drawing placed onto a metal plate. A scholar (I feel like we're going to be seeing a lot of scholars) is sent a Mezzotint of what appears to be just a normal house. However, each time the picture is left by itself and then later looked at it changes. The changes are subtle at first but quickly escalate. The race to find the house featured in the Mezzotint is exciting. Do the changes show an event from the past or does it predict the future? Awesome story.<br /> <br />The Ash-Tree: A woman accused of witchcraft is put to death. Was she? (Yep, and it does not end well for the accuser or his ancestors) Good stuff.<br /> <br />Number 13: A scholar (see I told you!) stays in a boarding house while he performs his research in town. He stays in room number 12 and notices that the room next to his is room 14....or is it? Where is room 13? Is there something creepy going on here? Does it tie into his research? I think you know the answers. Good stuff. Lovecraft clearly took some notes when he read this one.<br /> <br />Count Magnus: Is the spirit of a cruel former lord of the manor still around? Take a wild guess folks. Spooky and awesome.<br /><br />'Oh, Whistle, and I'll Come to You, My Lad': Previously reviewed in "Great Tales of Terror and the Supernatural."<br /><br />The Treasure of Abbot Thomas: I've always loved a good treasure hunt! In this, a holy man back in the 1600's left some clues in his church as to where he buried a huge amount of gold. A modern day scholar (that's right gang, another scholar!) is the first to decipher the clues. It gives the location of the treasure but warns that he has "placed a guardian over them." The scholar finds the location and more than he bargained for, and, oh yeah, probably loses his mind in the process. Good times!<br /> <br />A School Story: This is two old gentlement remembering scary stories of their youth. One recounts a tale of an old professor her had that had a mysterious coin on the end of a chain with initials and a date inscribed upon it. Someone or something is not happy that the professor has it and is willing to go to increasingly scary lengths to make this known. Less is definitely more in this little gem.<br /> <br />The Rose Garden: A woman wants to place a new rose garden on a piece of land that has a shady past. It brings new meaning to the phrase "Judge not least ye be judged." Creepy and great.<br /> <br />The Tractate Middoth: A librarian gets embroiled in a plot involving an old Hebrew book, a missing will, and an angry old son-of-a-bitch who won't stay dead. One of the few legitimately happy endings I've ever read in a scary story.<br /><br />Casting the Runes: An interesting tale of a cursed man trying to save himself. Great villain and quite a satisfying conclusion.<br /><br />The Stalls of Barchester Cathedral: A holy man slowly suspects three sinister looking wooden sculptures mean him harm. You can probably guess whether or not he's right. Good stuff.<br /><br />Martin's Close: I'm loving the framing devices of his stories. This begins with someone taking a tour of a large property and seeing an oddly, secluded area which leads to a flashback story of a gentleman carelessly playing with the affections of a simple-minded, homely country girl. She ends up murdered and he ends up on trial for it. To give anything else away would spoil the fun, but this is a great story!<br /><br />Mr. Humphreys and His Inheritance: I do so love a good story about a lawn maze! The aforementioned inheritor finds himself in possession of an estate which includes a locked, super spooky and mysterious lawn maze. If you need to know more to read this story then we are two very different people! Splendid stuff!<br /><br />The Residence at Whitminster: This story took a sharp right turn in the middle of it. I loved the first half about the malevolent young lord better than what followed but still and entertaining read.<br /><br />The Diary of Mr. Poynter: Haunted drapes!<br /><br />An Episode of Cathedral History: Another scholar goes snooping around an old cathedral and finds out some creepy business that has gone down there in the past. Is it a demon? Yes, it is a demon. Good stuff.<br /><br />The Story of a Disappearance and an Appearance: A strange story told through found letters (I love M.R. James framing devices!) of an unliked Uncle who goes missing right before Christmas and the nephew who tries to find him. An odd story that I think I would get more from if "Punch and Judy" was still a popular thing. I know that sounds like an odd then to say but read the story and you'll get it.<br /><br />Two Doctors: This story has everything: Evil magic. Pod People. Mysterious deaths. The story is told through found deposition testimony of all things. I can see the structure and ideas of this story in many horror tales/movies that have followed.<br /><br />The Haunted Dolls' House: A less scary version of "The Mezzotint." M.R. James even admits as much at the end of the story. Not my favorite.<br /><br />The Uncommon Prayer-Book: Haunted Bible!<br /><br />A Neighbour's Landmark: A fantastically creepy story about cursed soul and a haunted forest. And it all begins with a deceptively simple expression: "That which walks in Betton Wood Knows why it walks or why it cries." Great stuff.<br /><br />A View from a Hill: Binoculars that can see in the past...but at what price? (It's a bad price. Spoiler alert, the price is bad.)<br /><br />A Warning to the Curious: A young man digs up an ancient crown which may or may not be cursed. Saw a lot of spots later used by H.P. Lovecraft and Stephen King in this one. Very good stuff.<br /><br />An Evening's Entertainment: Ol' Grandma telling the kids a ghost story by the fire. Odd morality tale that seems like a veiled criticism of homosexuality. Some creepy images but mostly a very odd story.<br /><br />There Was a Man Dwelt by a Churchyard: This one was based on an off-hand line from Shakespeare's "The Winter's Tale." A character begins a story with this line only to be interrupted and is never allowed to finish the story. James took it upon himself to do so. An old miser lives by a graveyard and sees that some gold is buried with a body. You can probably guess what happens, but this is a short, sweet, and spooky story.<br /><br />Rats: A young scholar (because of course) stays in a small Inn to do some reading. There is a mysterious locked room that he just has to get into. What does he find inside? Spoiler alert: Not rats, oddly enough. Good stuff.<br /><br />After Dark in the Playing Fields: Incredibly strange, almost Shakespearean tale about a talking Owl in the dead of night. This one uses a lot of humor with mixed results.<br /><br />Wailing Well: A morality tale about one good Boy Scout and one bad Boy Scout. This would be a good camp fire story for kids because the bad scout gets punished severely and there is a fair amount of humor throughout to keep the kids interested.<br /><br />The Experiment: A rather boring and rather short resurrection story.<br /><br />The Malice of Inanimate Objects: The original "Final Destination." Be careful shaving...<br /><br />A Vignette: There's a spooky path near a church. Short and not at all scary.<br /><br />This was great stuff and I could definitely see where Lovecraft got his inspiration. Whereas James was most terrified of ancient religious history and knowing too much, Lovecraft was more concerned with ancient alien/monster history and knowing too much. Although a word of warning, don't try to read this book straight through. Much like Lovecraft, you'll need to take breaks with different books lest you get burned out. That being said, a strong recommend to anyone who likes a good scary story on a dark and stormy night.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6903733433058654043" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


