  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_708460437" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/708460437" />
    <a title="Issicratea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23268828-issicratea"><img alt="Issicratea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1378040602p2/23268828.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/708460437?book_show_action=true">Aug 31, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Issicratea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Issicratea" href="/user/show/23268828-issicratea">Issicratea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23268828-issicratea?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23268828-issicratea?shelf=1900-1950">1900-1950</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer708460437" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1376946960359017285">My view of this author changed considerably in the course of my reading of this collection. I embarked on it as a follow-up to the magnificent <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/551454.Tales_of_Hoffmann' title='Tales of Hoffmann by E.T.A. Hoffmann' rel='nofollow noopener'>Tales of Hoffmann</a>, and, at first, by comparison, it seemed distinctly lightweight, though engaging and fun to read. I became more and more intrigued by these stories as I went along, though. They’re deceptively simple, and M. R. himself quite determinedly played down their importance in his few critical remarks on them (“The stories … do not make any very</span>
  <span id="freeText1376946960359017285" style="display:none">My view of this author changed considerably in the course of my reading of this collection. I embarked on it as a follow-up to the magnificent <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/551454.Tales_of_Hoffmann" title="Tales of Hoffmann by E.T.A. Hoffmann" rel="nofollow noopener">Tales of Hoffmann</a>, and, at first, by comparison, it seemed distinctly lightweight, though engaging and fun to read. I became more and more intrigued by these stories as I went along, though. They’re deceptively simple, and M. R. himself quite determinedly played down their importance in his few critical remarks on them (“The stories … do not make any very exalted claim”). There is a lot to them, however, singly and, still more, collectively. I read an academic article when I finished reading throwing the combined weight of Benjamin, Baudrillard, Derrida, and Kristeva at them (Penny Fielding, “Reading Rooms: M. R. James and the Library of Modernity”, <i>MFS Modern Fiction Studies</i>, 46/3 (2000)), and it didn’t seem at all a case of using a hammer to crack a nut. <br /><br />M. R. James was a medieval historian and bibliophile—he’s still a familiar name in Cambridge as he compiled the first modern catalogues of the college libraries (all of them, incredibly enough)—and there’s something rather donnish in his style. Academics, antiquarians, librarians, book-collectors are the protagonists of many of his stories; typically, they make some kind of discovery in the course of their researches that unlocks an evil force from the distant or proximate past. These stories are conventionally described as ghost stories, but the evils unleashed are just as often demons or fiends or nameless horrors as they are conventional ghosts. The genre is really more “curse of the Pharoah” than ghost.<br /><br />Here’s how James describes his literary formula (the edition I used, Oxford World Classics’s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/255371.Casting_the_Runes_and_Other_Ghost_Stories" title="Casting the Runes and Other Ghost Stories by M.R. James" rel="nofollow noopener">Casting the Runes and Other Ghost Stories</a>, has an interesting collection of his critical statements as an appendix):<br /><br /><i>Let us … be introduced to the actors in a placid way; let us see them going about their ordinary business, undisturbed by forebodings, pleased with their surroundings; and into this calm environment let the ominous thing put out its head, unobtrusively at first, and then more insistently, until it holds the stage.</i><br /><br />He emphasizes pacing and crescendo here, and he’s a real master of them; in fact, his writing is generally excellent, in an unobtrusive kind of way. “Reticence” seems to be one of his key aesthetic principles, and at his best he exploits it brilliantly, pulling away from the horror at just the right moment to let your imagination take over and do the rest.<br /><br />The “ordinary business” of the stories, as James calls it, the scene-setting, can seem conventional to the point of banality—dusty old bachelors (or middle-aged bachelors or young bachelors) pottering round libraries, staying on their own in out-of-the-way seaside resorts, or entertaining themselves with a round of golf. The banality is the point, though, obviously; it’s the contrast between the stolidity of the protagonists and the uncanniness of the ancient horrors they unwittingly conjure up that is the pivot of the stories. The dynamic is that of the return of the repressed, and it’s perhaps not surprising that James’s nasties have such a distinctly sexual character (there’s a lot of hairiness and wetness and sliminess and dark holes—need I go on?) The article I cited above goes on about this at some length.<br /><br />One thing I found intriguing in the book, as a historian of sorts myself, was James’s inquest in these stories into his own profession. The protagonists are close enough to him in professional and lifestyle terms to function as self-parodies, and their impulse to unearth things best left unearthed (epitomized in the superb “A Warning to the Curious”) is clearly also some kind of parody of the curiosity about the past that fueled his own research. It is almost always physical artifacts from the past, of the type James was used to working with, that act as vehicles or triggers for the revenant horrors in these stories— books, an ancient whistle, a mezzotint, a maze, a stained-glass window. James conveys very well the intrinsic uncanniness of the past, and its undeadness, and the eerie charisma of its surviving physical relics. I remember discussing once with my students why handling old books is such a peculiar and compelling sensory experience. We didn’t get very far in analyzing it, but I think I could do better now having read James.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1376946960359017285" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review708460437">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
