    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2868862992" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2868862992" />
    <a title="John Adams" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58175327-john-adams"><img alt="John Adams" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1496479523p2/58175327.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2868862992?book_show_action=true">Jul 12, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Adams" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Adams" href="/user/show/58175327-john-adams">John Adams</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58175327-john-adams?shelf=horror">horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2868862992" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11387459265751803101">Many writers have strayed into the realm of the ghost story during their careers but few have made their name entirely within its borders. M R James is one such writer.<br/><br/>Montague Rhodes James was the son of an English clergyman. He was educated at Eton and Cambridge. He then spent his working life directing the Fitzwilliam Museum in Cambridge and as the university&apos;s vice-chancellor. Later in life he gave that up to take the post of provost at Eton. He died in 1936.<br/><br/>M R James was a lifelong scholar </span>
  <span id="freeText11387459265751803101" style="display:none">Many writers have strayed into the realm of the ghost story during their careers but few have made their name entirely within its borders. M R James is one such writer.<br /><br />Montague Rhodes James was the son of an English clergyman. He was educated at Eton and Cambridge. He then spent his working life directing the Fitzwilliam Museum in Cambridge and as the university's vice-chancellor. Later in life he gave that up to take the post of provost at Eton. He died in 1936.<br /><br />M R James was a lifelong scholar with a close connection to the Church of England. This was the world he moved in all his life - academic, antiquary studies and Christian faith - and his stories are drenched in authentic detail.<br /><br />In Canon Alberic's Scrapbook, Dennistoun visits St Bertrand de Comminges in southern France. He meets with the sacristan and is given a guided tour. At the man's house afterwards Dennistoun is shown a scrapbook collected by the late canon of the church. The old man had cannibalised countless unique manuscripts and gathered the disparate pages together as a keepsake. Dennistoun bids for the item - and can't believe how cheaply he is able to secure it. That should make him think twice but of course he's far too excited by the find to be able to do so, something that he ends up regretting.<br /><br />In The Mezzotint, Williams is a Cambridge academic who loves collecting rare art and other cultural items. He is sent a mezzotint on approval. It costs two guineas but appears to be nothing special. He consults a colleague at his college to see if there's something about the picture he's missing to explain the high price. It turns out that there is!<br /><br />"It was indubitable - rankly impossible, no doubt, but absolutely certain. In the middle of the lawn, in front of the unknown house, there was a figure where no figure had been at five o'clock that afternoon."<br /><br />In M R James's stories it is often a cultural object that is either haunted or is the conduit for an evil power. In other stories the powerful object is more mundane. For example, in The Rose Garden a post dug out the ground is all that remains of an old summerhouse. A child who grew up there had reason to be wary of the power it used to exert over her and her brother:<br /><br />"Neither of us would ever be here alone when we were children, and I'm not sure that I should care about it now in certain moods...I can tell you after a fashion what it was that gave us - well, almost a horror of the place when we were alone."<br /><br />The Wordsworth Classics version of this collection describes M R James as the finest ghost story writer England has ever produced. I think they might be right!<br /><br />Enjoy!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11387459265751803101" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

