<div id="review_744399105" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/744399105" />
    <a title="Linda Burnham" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7414679-linda-burnham"><img alt="Linda Burnham" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1515724813p2/7414679.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/744399105?book_show_action=true">Oct 18, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Linda Burnham" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Linda Burnham" href="/user/show/7414679-linda-burnham">Linda Burnham</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer744399105" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7345425826389890889">These stories took me back to my childhood, holidays at the beach in old houses, howling winds and the crashing of the waves at night. Four children whiling away the evening hours reading ghost stories from books borrowed from the local library. <br/>A childhood filled with the fairies and talking animals and tales of adventuring children garnered from the works of English authors who dominated our childish world view at that time.<br/>These ghost stories of M R James are the stuff of children&apos;s nightmare</span>
  <span id="freeText7345425826389890889" style="display:none">These stories took me back to my childhood, holidays at the beach in old houses, howling winds and the crashing of the waves at night. Four children whiling away the evening hours reading ghost stories from books borrowed from the local library. <br />A childhood filled with the fairies and talking animals and tales of adventuring children garnered from the works of English authors who dominated our childish world view at that time.<br />These ghost stories of M R James are the stuff of children's nightmares and fears, the lurking presence on the other side of the door, the hand that may grab you if you reach to close the window at night, the words of an ancient book which may or may not summon something dark and terrifying when read aloud by unsuspecting lips.<br />By today's standards these stories do not manage to terrify but in the context of their time, when so much of life was yet to be subjected to the scrutiny of science and laid bare by the 20th century's media and entertainment revolution, they send a chill up the spine and send one scuttling quickly through darkened hallways to regain the perceived security of the light and warmth and comfort of one's own bedroom.<br />M R James is truly the master of the chillingly accessible ghost story, the story that is told of someone not so different from oneself or one's acquaintance or family and in this way, probably the grandfather of the Urban Myth.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7345425826389890889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


