    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1417804674" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1417804674" />
    <a title="Benjamin Stahl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16968146-benjamin-stahl"><img alt="Benjamin Stahl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1631332745p2/16968146.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1417804674?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Benjamin Stahl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Benjamin Stahl" href="/user/show/16968146-benjamin-stahl">Benjamin Stahl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/394836.Collected_Ghost_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1417804674" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15077019105741774944">I was introduced to M.R. James after reading <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1577098.The_Wordsworth_Book_Of_Horror_Stories__Special_Editions_' title='The Wordsworth Book Of Horror Stories (Special Editions) by Alice Askew' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Wordsworth Book Of Horror Stories</a> - a gargantuan compilation of horror tales written between the eighteenth and twentieth centuries. It contained many obscure treasures by authors all over England, Europe and America. I even recall there being an Australian in there as well. Of course, the book was slow-going at times. But overall, I found it thrillingly scary and enchanting to read. Along with Bram Stoker&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17245.Dracula' title='Dracula by Bram Stoker' rel='nofollow noopener'>Dracula</a>, it is what ignited my love not</span>
  <span id="freeText15077019105741774944" style="display:none">I was introduced to M.R. James after reading <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1577098.The_Wordsworth_Book_Of_Horror_Stories__Special_Editions_" title="The Wordsworth Book Of Horror Stories (Special Editions) by Alice Askew" rel="nofollow noopener">The Wordsworth Book Of Horror Stories</a> - a gargantuan compilation of horror tales written between the eighteenth and twentieth centuries. It contained many obscure treasures by authors all over England, Europe and America. I even recall there being an Australian in there as well. Of course, the book was slow-going at times. But overall, I found it thrillingly scary and enchanting to read. Along with Bram Stoker's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17245.Dracula" title="Dracula by Bram Stoker" rel="nofollow noopener">Dracula</a>, it is what ignited my love not just for "pre-modern" horror fiction, but classic literature in general. I have never forgiven myself for giving the book away, since then, to some charity shop or perhaps my church, so that some other lucky schmuck can get hold of it. If anyone has this on their shelves, or ever comes across it in a second-hand bookstore, I would highly recommend buying it. It’s easily worth $50 at least, and yet I got it new for a mere twenty bucks. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1446205909i/16765059.jpg" width='“500"' height='“200"' alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12927558-the-wordsworth-book-of-horror-stories">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1...</a><br><br>Among many other literary greats like Doyle, Dickens, Le Fanu and Scrotum, this book featured an inconsistent concentration of James’s work. But all the better for it. I remember being mesmerised with almost every one of his stories. That was back in 2010 or somewhere thereof, and apart from reading <i>Oh, Whistle</i> once more in another compilation, I haven’t come across any of his stuff then. That is, until this book, which I was more than excited to read. <br><br>Revisiting <i>Dracula</i>) a second time, the experience could not have been more rewarding, and I was certain that I would love this guy’s short but chilling work just as much, if not more, on reading it again. <br><br>Unfortunately, things didn’t turn out quite that way. And it still hurts and baffles me to say this. But I don’t mean any disrespect to James, because this book was, by all means, most enjoyable, and often scary. It just didn’t live up to the greatness that I have, until now, attributed to his work. I understand that many still idolise him, and I suppose I still do as well. It’s just that I don’t think I would call him one of my favourites anymore. The point is, on revisiting what pretty much makes up the entirety his work, I found myself enjoying it hardly more than I have similar compilations of the likes of Rudyard Kipling, Robert Louis Stevenson, and Wilkie Collins. There were a number of really great stories, but overall I think most of them started to feel too repetitive and not altogether satisfying in the end.<br><br>Firstly, I’ll just list my favourite ones, which I had nothing against. These were all genuinely creepy, or at least interesting. <i>Lost Hearts</i> - which I’m sure I hadn’t read before, and this one was quite creepy (I also liked the black humour in the story’s title). <i>The Ash Tree</i> was average at first, but the ending stayed with me a night or two. <i>Number 13</i>, again, was actually pretty average, but for a few little touches that made it hard to shake off (like, for instance, the image of that door suddenly opening slightly, and the arm reaching out and clawing at the air).<br> <br><i>Oh Whistle, And I’ll Come To You, My Lad</i>, I always considered to be James’s equivalent of Bierce’s <i>An Occurrence At Owl Creek Bridge</i>, in that it was certainly decent, but not deserving as being his most famous story, because he had several superior ones out there. Well, after reading this a third time - and alongside all his other stories - I think I’ll finally comply with the majority now. This probably is his best story. <br><br><i>The Tractate Middoth</i> and <i>Casting The Runes</i> were similar in that neither was all that frightening, but I certainly got involved in the character’s plight in each work. And then there was <i>An Episode Of Cathedral History</i>, which was actually another pretty freaky story - despite its quite unpromising title. <br><br>These stories were all great. And, to be fair, there weren’t any <i>bad</i> entries in this book. But there were many that just seemed way too average to be given much thought or credit. Certain tropes of James become a little too noticeable when you read a large amount of his work in direct sequence. I found it kind of annoying how so many of his stories began on the “<i>it happened to a friend of a friend of a colleague of mine</i>” premise. Also, James was often very good at building suspense and setting his atmosphere perfectly ... only to break the subtlety by bringing some ludicrous "hairy monster" into the equation. (Many of his stories’ monsters were described as being covered in grey hairs, and wearing dark cloaks. I don't know what his problem was, but he was terrified of these things. God, it's a good thing he died before Star Wars came out). This was all fine the first couple of times, but after a while it got too silly to take seriously. <br><br>I also found - and I could be overstepping here, holding my personal failings against him - that his descriptions of geographical landscapes were a bit dry and uninspired. I found myself having to pause and strain my mind to picture his locales more clearly, because he didn’t give me much, and what he <i>did</i> give me - things like the architectural features of churches and mansion exteriors - I just didn’t understand the anatomies for in the first place, and so found myself picturing, for most of these stories, backdrops no less vague than something presented in a high-school play. <br><br>None of these are exactly major flaws, but they did get in the way of my relishing the book as much as I wanted to. But all in all, I still can’t bring myself to say anything against M.R. James. I still admire the man, and I still love his period of horror fiction. I just think that, in retrospect, reading the book from start to finish might not have been the best idea. Like pretty much all the greats, his work is more easily appreciated when consumed in smaller doses. After all, that is how he originally gave them to the world ... having his students gather around the fire each Christmas and relating a story prepared for the occasion. There are few ideas more appealing than being in on those private occasions. He must have given many young boy a nightmare in his day. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15077019105741774944" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


