<div id="review_721156238" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/721156238" />
    <a title="Sam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72837-sam"><img alt="Sam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1178153459p2/72837.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/721156238?book_show_action=true">Sep 16, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sam" href="/user/show/72837-sam">Sam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer721156238" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8035643317131114461">Assigned this book for a class on Freud&apos;s Uncanny and Horror Literature, and had a tough time presenting James in such a way that the students got beyond his &quot;reasonable&quot; facade and into deeper, weirder territory. Yes, James is a master of &quot;understatement&quot; - although I wonder if this isn&apos;t just a function of the narrative layers and frames he&apos;s so fond of employing - but he uses this light touch to investigate some deeper strain of desire. All of these academics, desperate to uncover previously </span>
  <span id="freeText8035643317131114461" style="display:none">Assigned this book for a class on Freud's Uncanny and Horror Literature, and had a tough time presenting James in such a way that the students got beyond his "reasonable" facade and into deeper, weirder territory. Yes, James is a master of "understatement" - although I wonder if this isn't just a function of the narrative layers and frames he's so fond of employing - but he uses this light touch to investigate some deeper strain of desire. All of these academics, desperate to uncover previously buried secrets, get exactly what they deserve in the form of demons, "hairy hopping things," a whole array of (unwanted?) physical touch from loathsome, tentacled members. In other words, the deeper one investigates James' unconscious territory the more interesting the stories become. I particularly enjoyed "Count Magnus," which so enthralled H.P. Lovecraft, both in its calm deployment of a frame and the eventual destruction of the frame by the desire for access to history, as if the characters are desperate to reach through a picture and inhabit it, only to have the figures in the painting reach out to them. <br />Adventures at the edge of "forbidden" knowledge, frustrated desire, and the appearance of the shadowy demon double. No better arena for the dissolution of the bourgeois subject than horror literature, amiright? Loved this book. Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8035643317131114461" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


