  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_487726879" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/487726879" />
    <a title="Lisa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14819128-lisa"><img alt="Lisa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1412502384p2/14819128.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/487726879?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lisa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lisa" href="/user/show/14819128-lisa">Lisa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/11710847-collected-ghost-stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14819128-lisa?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14819128-lisa?shelf=2013-reads">2013-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14819128-lisa?shelf=ghosts">ghosts</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer487726879" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12426640382755309119">I was not too sure what to expect from this book at first but I really did enjoy it. It&apos;s a collection of 30 short stories by the man who is considered by many to be the original (and the best) ghost writer and, on the whole, it does not disappoint.<br/>The stories were written getting on for 100 years ago and as a result, are written in the &apos;antiquarian&apos; style that was popular at the time which I thought worked really well, particulary when you consider the historical settings of many of the stories</span>
  <span id="freeText12426640382755309119" style="display:none">I was not too sure what to expect from this book at first but I really did enjoy it. It's a collection of 30 short stories by the man who is considered by many to be the original (and the best) ghost writer and, on the whole, it does not disappoint.<br />The stories were written getting on for 100 years ago and as a result, are written in the 'antiquarian' style that was popular at the time which I thought worked really well, particulary when you consider the historical settings of many of the stories. I personally found the book pretty easy to read, although the Victorian/Edwardian writing style did take a bit of getting used to over the first couple of stories. The stories are short in length but M R James manages to set the scene very quickly in each story and also manages to pack a lot of description into each story and the result is that you can pretty much always picture the locations/scenery and the characters in your head.<br />So, is the book scary? It is but in a very subtle way. I would describe it as more chilling than anything else. A lot is left to the reader's imagination when it comes to the ghosts/spectres/creatures and what their motives and back stories might be and I personally enjoyed this aspect of the writing, I like the fact that M R James keeps some things back and let's the reader form their own theories and conclusions as to what might be going on. Some stories are more scary/creepy than others and the ones which I found to be the most creepy were 'Oh, Whistle, And I'll Come To You, My Lad', 'Number 13', 'Mr Humphreys and His Inheritance' and, probably due to the fact that I don't like dolls or puppets very much, 'The Story of a Disappearance and an Appearance' and 'The Haunted Dolls House' , although pretty much every story in this book (with a couple of exceptions) has it's 'shiver down the spine' moments.<br />The reason why I gave this book 4 stars is because there were a few stories within this book that I did not enjoy as much as the others such as 'The Residence at Whitminster' and 'After Dark in the Playing Fields' and this was largely due to the fact that I found them to be a little bit short on chills and thrills and I ended up feeling a bit indifferent towards them. They were not bad by any means but I would skip over them should I read this book again (and I expect I will).<br />Overall, this was a very entertaining and enjoyable book that certainly has its fair share of spooky moments. If you are looking for some old-fashioned ghost stories that chill rather than terrify, are not full of blood and gore and let you draw your own conclusions then I would recommend checking this book out.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12426640382755309119" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review487726879">
